      <title>Massive bubble of hot rock detected beneath New England</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEA new study has found that the idyllic New England region could eventually become a hotbed of volcanic activity.Using data from earthquake measurement devices, Rutgers University researchers analyzed the speed and direction of seismic waves to visualize subsurface conditions.According to a university press release, they detected a massive upwelling of hot rock under Vermont, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts, after noticing the area was noticeably hotter than neighboring regions.Though the hot mass is slowly and steadily rising, it will take millions of years before it reaches the surface and reshapes the area's geography or create a volcano.Scientists say what's happening in New England may be similar to the onset of the Yellowstone supervolcano.It emphasizes how intricate and dynamic the Earth's subsurface features are, and definitely warrants further study.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Researchers analyzed seismic waves to visualize subsurface conditions2. Mass of hot rock detected under Vermont, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts3. Hot rock rising slowly, could eventually lead to region becoming volcanically active 4. Potential volcanic eruptions possible, but won't be for millions of yearsVOICEOVER (in English): "Using data from earthquake measurement devices, Rutgers University researchers analyzed the speed and direction of seismic waves to visualize subsurface conditions.""They detected a massive upwelling of hot rock under Vermont, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts, after noticing the area was noticeably hotter than neighboring regions.""Though the hot mass is slowly and steadily rising, it will take millions of years before it reaches the surface and reshapes the area's geography or create a volcano."SOURCES: Rutgers University, National Geographic, Forbeshttps://news.rutgers.edu/research-news/mass-warm-rock-rising-beneath-new-england-rutgers-study-suggests/20171121#.WidNtoiGOUlhttps://news.nationalgeographic.com/2017/12/magma-bubble-rising-under-new-england-volcanoes-science/https://www.forbes.com/sites/trevornace/2017/12/05/enormous-pool-of-molten-rock-found-rising-beneath-new-england/#6bc482b6273e***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
