      <title>Amazon patents self-destructing delivery drones</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEAmazon has been granted a patent for self-destructing delivery drones in case of mid-air emergencies.The company filed the patent last year, according to New Atlas. In addition to a person controlling the drone's flightpath, the drone would also have a "fragmentation controller" responsible for breaking the drone apart if needed. The fragmentation controller would detect any drone error and come up with a "fragmentation sequence" in order to determine which parts should be broken off the machine. The controller would need to be able to track the flight path, weather conditions and topography to determine what parts can be released.  RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Amazon delivery drone delivering a package2. Drone operator controlling the delivery drone3. Amazon drone falling apart during a fragmentation sequence4. Drone fragmentation controller has the ability to track flight path, weather and topographyVOICEOVER (in English): "Amazon has been granted a patent for self-destructing delivery drones in case of mid-air emergencies." "In addition to a person controlling the drone's flightpath, the drone would also have a 'fragmentation controller' responsible for breaking the drone apart if needed." "The fragmentation controller would detect any drone error and come up with a 'fragmentation sequence' in order to determine which parts should be broken off the machine." "The controller would need to be able to track the flight path, weather conditions and topography to determine what parts can be released." SOURCES: New Atlas, NBC Newshttps://newatlas.com/amazon-delivery-drones-self-destuct/52456/https://www.nbcnews.com/mach/science/amazon-drone-designed-self-destruct-emergencies-here-s-why-ncna826246***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
