      <title>Scientists call for ban on glitter</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEEnvironmental experts are calling for a worldwide ban on glitter amidst concerns that it is hazardous to the environment.Fortune reports that glitter is made from millimeter-sized bits of a polymer called polyethylene terephthalate or PET, or sometimes known as mylar. Scientists consider it a microplastic, and say it should be banned.Glitter filters into the oceans, where it gets mistaken for food by fish and other sea creatures, and can leach out harmful chemicals into the marine environment.A 2014 study estimated that the world's seas contain roughly 5.25 trillion pieces of plastic trash, with microplastics accounting for 92.4%.The UK is set to officially ban items that contain tiny plastics called microbeads by 2018, with other countries also following suit.Some British nurseries have already taken up the call to give up glitter, and banned the use of the product in their facilities. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Glitter is a microplastic, made from polymer called mylar2. Glitter filters into oceans, can cause harm to marine life3. Microplastics make up 92.4% of the trillions of plastic trash polluting the oceans4. UK to officially ban items that contain microbeads in 2018VOICEOVER (in English): "Glitter is made from millimeter-sized bits of a polymer known as PET, or mylar. Scientists consider it a microplastic, and argue that it should be banned.""Glitter filters into the oceans, where it gets mistaken for food by fish and other sea creatures, and can leach out harmful chemicals into the marine environment.""A 2014 study estimated that the world's seas contain roughly 5.25 trillion pieces of plastic trash, with microplastics accounting for 92.4%""The UK is set to officially ban items that contain tiny plastics called microbeads by 2018, with other countries also following suit."SOURCES: Fortune, New York Times, U.S. National Library of Medicinehttp://fortune.com/2017/11/30/banning-glitter/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/30/style/glitter-ban.htmlhttps://toxtown.nlm.nih.gov/text_version/chemicals.php?id=96***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
