      <title>Electron rocket prepares second launch from New Zealand</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONERocket Lab has had to repeatedly postpone the test flight of their second Electron vehicle to Tuesday afternoon, after weather conditions and orbital traffic proved less than ideal on Monday.The New Zealand Herald reports that the electron rocket known as 'Still Testing' is currently at a launch site in New Zealand.  It's 17 meters long and can carry a 150-kilogram payload into orbit.The rocket will be launched into space from the Mahia Peninsula, with the first stage scheduled to separate and fall into the Pacific two and a half minutes into the flight.Three shoebox-sized satellites will then be released at 8 minutes, 31 seconds.The single Dove Pioneer CubeSat is an Earth-imaging satellite, while the two Lemur-2 satellites are used for weather mapping and ship traffic tracking.Rocket Labs successfully launched its first Electron rocket in May 2017, though it failed to reach orbit.The company originally planned three test flights, and will run a third test launch if needed.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Electron rocket is 17m long, can carry 150kg payload into orbit2. Rocket set for second launch attempt from Mahia Peninsula 3. Rocket will release three shoebox-sized satellites into space4. Satellites will be used for Earth imaging, weather mapping, and ship traffic trackingVOICEOVER (in English): "The Electron rocket known as 'Still Testing' is currently at a launch site in New Zealand.  It's 17 meters long and can carry a 150-kilogram payload into orbit.""The rocket will be launched into space from the Mahia Peninsula, with the first stage scheduled to separate and fall into the Pacific two and a half minutes into the flight.""Three shoebox-sized satellites will then be released at 8 minutes, 31 seconds.""The single Dove Pioneer CubeSat is an Earth-imaging satellite, while the two Lemur-2 satellites are used for weather mapping and ship traffic tracking."SOURCES: New Zealand Herald, Spaceflight Nowhttp://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11957268https://spaceflightnow.com/2017/12/07/rocket-lab-pushes-back-second-electron-launch-by-one-day/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
