      <title>Facebook is rolling out new facial recognition features</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEFacebook announced on Tuesday it will soon be introducing new facial recognition features in order to give users more tools to manage their identity on the platform. People will soon be able to activate facial recognition with an on/off switch to enable three different features, according to a Facebook blog post. First, Facebook will alert you when pictures of you are uploaded even if you have not been tagged in them, Gizmodo reported. Second, Facebook will notify you if your face is being used in a profile picture. Third, visually impaired users can now hear aloud the people tagged around them in group photos. To activate these features, users will have to authorize Facebook to access, store and match their face data with all uploads across the social media platform.   RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Facebook user having his face scanned2. Facebook's facial recognition can be turned on with an on/off switch3. Facial recognition will alert users when pictures of them have been uploaded or if their face is used for a profile picture 4. Visually impaired user listening to people tagged in photoVOICEOVER (in English): "Facebook announced on Tuesday it will soon be introducing new facial recognition features in order to give users more tools to manage their identity on the platform." "People will soon be able to activate facial recognition with an on/off switch to enable three different features, according to a Facebook blog post." "First, Facebook will alert you when pictures of you are uploaded even if you have not been tagged in them. Second, you will be notified if your face is being used as a profile picture.""Third, visually impaired users can now hear aloud the people tagged around them in group photos." SOURCES: Gizmodo, Facebookhttps://gizmodo.c