      <title>How serious is the anthrax threat from North Korea?</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONENew reports from South Korea have raised fears that Kim Jong Un's government may be using anthrax to develop biological weapons.CNN reports that one of at least four soldiers who defected from North Korea was found with anthrax antibodies in his system, suggesting he was either vaccinated, or exposed to the virus at some point.The North has also reportedly begun testing loading anthrax into intercontinental ballistic missiles, to determine whether the bacteria can withstand the high temperatures of atmospheric reentry.Anthrax is caused by exposure to Bacillus anthracis spores. It causes flu-like symptoms, and can kill 80% of those exposed within 24 hours, unless antibiotics are administered.South Korea's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention bought 1,000 doses of anthrax vaccine for agents or civilians. The Blue House  South Korea's executive office  has an additional 350, ordered by the previous government.Fears of a biochemical attack come just weeks before the South is set to host the 2018 Winter Olympics.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Soldier defected from North Korea found with anthrax antibodies2. North Korea tests loading anthrax on missiles3. Anthrax description and symptoms4. South Korea bought anthrax vaccines in case of exposureVOICEOVER (in English): "One of at least four soldiers who defected from North Korea had anthrax antibodies in his system, suggesting he was either vaccinated, or exposed to the virus at some point.""The North has also reportedly begun testing loading anthrax into intercontinental ballistic missiles, to determine whether the bacteria can withstand the high temperatures of atmospheric reentry.""Anthrax is caused by exposure to Bacillus anthracis spores. It causes flu-like symptoms, and can kill 80% of those exposed within 24 hours, unless antibiotics are administered.""South Korea's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention bought 1,000 doses of anthrax vaccine for agents or civilians. The Blue House  South Korea's executive office  has an additional 350, ordered by the previous government."SOURCES: CNN, Asahi Shimbun, USA Todayhttp://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/27/asia/north-korea-anthrax-intl/index.htmlhttp://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201712200036.htmlhttps://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2017/12/27/anthrax-defector-raises-new-fears-north-korea-developing-biological-weapons/983810001/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
